  "text": "The Kubernetes scheduler plugin framework is architected as follows:\n\n**Core Framework Interfaces (pkg/scheduler/framework/interface.go):**\nThe framework defines a Plugin parent interface (line 443) that all scheduler plugins implement. This is subclassed by extension point-specific plugins:\n- PreEnqueuePlugin: Called before adding pods to active queue\n- QueueSortPlugin: Sorts pods in the scheduling queue\n- PreFilterPlugin: Called at the beginning of the scheduling cycle\n- FilterPlugin (line 540): Filters out nodes that cannot run a pod (formerly called 'predicate')\n- PostFilterPlugin: Called after pod fails PreFilter or Filter\n- PreScorePlugin: Informational extension after filtering\n- ScorePlugin (line 607): Ranks filtered nodes with numeric scores\n- ReservePlugin: Updates plugin state (formerly 'assume')\n- PreBindPlugin: Called before binding\n- PermitPlugin: Called before binding to allow/delay binding\n- BindPlugin (line 673): Binds pod to a node\n- PostBindPlugin: Called after successful binding\n\nThe Framework interface (line 686) manages all plugins in use by the scheduling framework and exposes methods to invoke them.\n\n**Top-Level Scheduler (pkg/scheduler/scheduler.go, line 66):**\nThe Scheduler struct coordinates the entire scheduling process. It contains:\n- Cache: The node state cache\n- SchedulingQueue: Queue of pods to schedule\n- Profiles: Multiple scheduling profiles (framework.Map)\n- SchedulePod: Function that schedules a pod\n- FailureHandler: Handles scheduling failures\n\nThe Scheduler.Run method (line 464) starts the scheduling loop in a dedicated goroutine calling ScheduleOne repeatedly until context is done.\n\n**Orchestration Function (pkg/scheduler/schedule_one.go, line 65):**\nScheduleOne(ctx context.Context) does the entire scheduling workflow for a single pod:\n1. Gets next pod from SchedulingQueue\n2. Selects the appropriate scheduling profile/framework\n3. Runs PreFilter plugins via framework\n4. Filters nodes using FilterPlugins\n5. Runs PreScore and Score plugins to rank nodes\n6. Handles binding, permitting, and other post-score phases\nThis is serialized on the scheduling algorithm's host fitting.\n\n**Framework Runtime (pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/framework.go, line 52):**\nframeworkImpl is the component responsible for initializing and running scheduler plugins. It contains:\n- Plugin lists for each extension point (preFilterPlugins, filterPlugins, scorePlugins, bindPlugins, etc.)\n- Registry: Initialized plugins by name\n- SharedLister: Access to node information\n- SnapshotSharedLister: Current cluster state snapshot\n\nKey methods:\n- RunFilterPlugins (line 872): Runs the set of configured Filter plugins for a pod on a given node. Iterates through filterPlugins and returns status on first failure.\n- RunScorePlugins (line 1112): Runs all Score plugins in parallel across nodes. Each plugin scores all nodes, then results are normalized and aggregated.\n\nBoth methods handle metrics recording, logging at different verbosity levels, and check for skipped plugins via CycleState.\n\n**Plugin Registry (pkg/scheduler/framework/plugins/registry.go, line 47):**\nNewInTreeRegistry() builds the registry with all in-tree plugins, returning runtime.Registry (line 47). It includes:\n- dynamicresources, imagelocality, tainttoleration, nodename, nodeports, nodeaffinity, podtopologyspread, nodeunschedulable, noderesources (fit and balanced allocation), volumebinding, volumerestrictions, volumezone, nodevolumelimits, interpodaffinity, queuesort, defaultbinder, defaultpreemption, schedulinggates\n\nEach plugin is registered with the registry using its factory function or FactoryAdapter (for feature gate support). The registry can be extended with out-of-tree plugins via WithFrameworkOutOfTreeRegistry option.\n\n**Execution Chain:**\nScheduler.Run() -> ScheduleOne() -> framework.RunFilterPlugins() -> framework.RunScorePlugins() -> binding phase plugins. The frameworkImpl manages all plugin lifecycle and invocation at each extension point in the scheduling cycle."
}

